viewed as normal—or maybe even excessive? I’m not entirely sure. There aren't any source stubs available right now, but it seems we could dynamically create an agent jar. I think I need to compile imports involving com.sun.tools.attach.VirtualMachine to make that work smoothly. It's a bit of a technical puzzle, but I think I'm on the right track!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class structures**\\n\\nI'm exploring whether the Agent-Class can use a nested class name with a `$` in the manifest. From my tests, it seems file names are fine even if the test class doesn't have a `$`. The manifest can contain a `$`, which makes sense. However, the Agent class must be declared public static, and the top-level test should also be public. It looks like nested classes need to be public static too.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering ByteBuddy options**\\n\\nI’ve previously passed tests, but now I need to check if I can directly access ByteBuddy internals for packages with opens to cover package methods. There's a chance this might not work as intended. The user wants the functionality to be active, though, so that’s crucial. I wonder if I could include optional features only if reflection is available. It’s tricky, but I'll explore these options further!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_F9DesOetFS3KFakaZGMxLmcU|fc_079fc6a7bc1ecf8e016a25f6534d448190b67faca25644b918", "name": "write", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.assertj/assertj-core/3.22.0/src/test/java/org_assertj/assertj_core/ClassInjectorInnerUsingReflectionInnerDispatcherInnerUsingUnsafeInjectionTest.java", "content": "/*\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\n *\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\n */\npackage org_assertj.assertj_core;\n\nimport static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertEquals;\n\nimport java.io.IOException;\nimport java.io